.LI "\fBNAME\fP"
.br
basename, dirname - return a portion of a path name
.LI "\fBSYNOPSIS\fP"
.br
.EX
\#include <sblib.h>

.SO pathname.dd
.EE
.LI "\fBDESCRIPTION\fP"
.br
The \*(Bn and \*(Dn functions parse a UNIX path name and return the
file component and directory component, respectively.  The \fIpath\fP
argument is a pointer to a NULL terminated character string.  Directories
and files in the \fIpath\fP are separated by the slash ('/') character.
The \fIbuffer\fP argument is a pointer to a memory location large enough
to hold the file or directory component plus a NULL.
.P
If path or buffer is NULL, both functions will return NULL.
.P
If \fIpath\fP contains no slash characters, \*(Bn copies \fIpath\fP
into \fIbuffer\fP.
If \fIpath\fP contains slash characters, \*(Bn copies the characters after
the last slash into \fIbuffer\fP.
In both cases \fIbuffer\fP is NULL terminated and \*(Bn
returns \fIbuffer\fP for the convenience of the application using it.
.P
If \fIpath\fP contains no slash characters, \*(Dn puts a dot ('.', current
directory) into \fIbuffer\fP.
If \fIpath\fP contains slash characters, \*(Dn copies all the characters
before the last slash into \fIbuffer\fP.
In both cases \fIbuffer\fP is NULL terminated and \*(Dn
returns \fIbuffer\fP for the convenience of the application using it.
.LE
